Here's a typical approach:

## 1. Define theme resource dictionaries

Create a separate `ResourceDictionary` XAML file for each theme:

```xml
<!-- Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Repeat for `DarkTheme.xaml` and `HighContrastTheme.xaml` with different values but **the same keys**.

## 2. Create a theme service

```csharp
public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        var mergedDictionaries = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove the current theme dictionary (always the last one added)
        var existing = mergedDictionaries.LastOrDefault(d => d is ThemeDictionary);
        if (existing is not null)
            mergedDictionaries.Remove(existing);

        ResourceDictionary theme = themeName switch
        {
            "Dark" => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast" => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _ => new LightTheme()
        };

        mergedDictionaries.Add(theme);

        // Persist choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", themeName);
    }
}
```

> Mark each theme class with `x:Class` so it compiles to a type you can instantiate.

## 3. Apply on startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light"));
}
```

## 4. Settings page picker

```xml
<Picker Title="Theme" SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>HighContrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (sender is Picker p && p.SelectedItem is string theme)
        ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
}
```

## 5. Consume theme colors in XAML

```xml
<Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" />
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}" />
```

**Key point:** Use `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) so bindings update immediately when the dictionary is swapped at runtime.

---

This gives you instant theme switching with no page reload or app restart required.
